actions.comment:
Thanks for the detailed report and stack trace.

The crash is caused by a memory leak in the snapshot pattern. Each call to `Surface.Snapshot()` copies all pixel data from the surface — for an 8000×2000 canvas, that's ~64MB per snapshot. Since `layerBackGround` is reassigned without disposing the previous `SKImage`, those ~64MB allocations accumulate until the WASM heap is exhausted (after ~34 iterations in your case).

Here's a workaround — dispose the old image before creating a new one:

```csharp
canvas.DrawImage(layerBackGround, rect1);

// Draw something permanent

layerBackGround?.Dispose();
layerBackGround = e.Surface.Snapshot();

// Draw something temporary
```

For your drag-and-drop use case, you might also consider using `SKPictureRecorder` instead of pixel snapshots. It records draw commands (very small) rather than copying the full pixel buffer, which scales much better on memory-constrained platforms like WASM.

See also #576 which describes the same pattern.
